To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that responds to a `/ban` slash command, follow these steps:

1. First, install the Discord.js library if you haven't already:
```bash
npm install discord.js
```

2. Create a new file, let's call it `bot.js`, and use the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
const { TOKEN } = require('./config.json'); // Make sure to create a config.json file with your bot token

// Initialize the client
const client = new Client({ intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers, GatewayIntentBits.GuildModeration] });

// Command setup
client.on('ready', () => {
    console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}`);

    // Register the ban command globally
    client.application.commands.register(new SlashCommandBuilder()
        .setName('ban')
        .setDescription('Bans a member from the server.')
        .addUserOption(option => option
            .setName('target')
            .setDescription('The member to ban.')
            .setRequired(true))
        .addStringOption(option => option
            .setName('reason')
            .setDescription('The reason for the ban.')
            .setRequired(false)));
});

// Command handler
client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
    if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

    if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
        if (!interaction.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
            return interaction.reply({ content: 'You do not have the permission to ban members.', ephemeral: true });
        }

        const target = interaction.options.getUser('target');
        const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

        try {
            await interaction.guild.members.ban(target, { reason });
            await interaction.reply(`Successfully banned ${target.tag} for: ${reason}`);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error(error);
            await interaction.reply('There was an error trying to ban that member.');
        }
    }
});

// Run the bot
client.login(TOKEN);
```

3. Create a `config.json` file in the same directory as `bot.js` and add your bot token:
```json
{
    "TOKEN": "your-bot-token-here"
}
```
Replace "your-bot-token-here" with your actual bot token, which you can get from the Discord Developer Portal.

4. Finally, run your bot with:
```bash
node bot.js
```

Make sure to invite your bot to your server with the necessary permissions, and you'll be able to use the `/ban` command. Remember that the bot will need the `Ban Members` permission, and you should enable the `Application Commands` feature in the Discord Developer Portal for your bot.

Converting Markdown to HTML involves parsing the Markdown syntax and translating it into corresponding HTML tags. This process can get quite complex depending on the extent of Markdown features you want to support. For simplicity, let's create a basic C++ function that converts a very limited subset of Markdown to HTML. This example will cover headers ( `#`, `##`, `###`, etc.) and emphasis (`*, **` for italic and bold respectively).

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHTML(const std::string &markdown) {
    // Header conversion
    std::regex headerRegex("^(#{1,6}) (.*)$");
    std::string headerReplace;
    for (int i = 1; i <= 6; ++i) {
        headerReplace.clear();
        headerReplace += "<h";
        headerReplace += std::to_string(i);
        headerReplace += ">";
        std::string pattern = "#";
        for (int j = 0; j < i; ++j) pattern += "#";
        headerReplace += std::string(pattern.length(), ' '); // Matching space
        headerReplace += "</h";
        headerReplace += std::to_string(i);
        headerReplace += ">";

        // Replace headers with HTML tags
        std::string replacement;
        std::regex_replace(std::back_inserter(replacement), markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), headerRegex, headerReplace);
        markdown = replacement;
    }

    // Emphasis conversion (italic and bold)
    std::regex emphasisRegex(R"((\*|__)(\S.*?\S)\1)"); // Captures text between * or __
    std::string emphasisReplace;
    for (char em = '*'; em <= '__'; ++em) {
        emphasisReplace.clear();
        emphasisReplace += "<";
        emphasisReplace += em == '*' ? "em" : "strong";
        emphasisReplace += ">";
        emphasisReplace += "</";
        emphasisReplace += em == '*' ? "em" : "strong";
        emphasisReplace += ">";

        // Replace emphasis with HTML tags
        std::string replacement;
        std::regex_replace(std::back_inserter(replacement), markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), emphasisRegex, emphasisReplace);
        markdown = replacement;
    }

    return markdown; // Return the converted string
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Heading 1\n## Heading 2\n***Emphasis***";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHTML(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This function uses C++'s `<regex>` library for pattern matching and replacement. It defines regular expressions for matching Markdown headers (from `#` to `######`) and emphasis (using `*` for italic and `__` for bold). Each match is replaced with the corresponding HTML tag.

Note: This is a very basic example. Markdown is a rich format with many more features (like lists, links, code blocks, etc.) that are not covered here. For full Markdown to HTML conversion, consider using existing libraries or tools that are specifically designed for this task.

Remember, when dealing with user input and generating HTML, it's crucial to sanitize the input to prevent security vulnerabilities like Cross-Site Scripting (XSS). This simple example does not sanitize input and should not be used as a basis for handling untrusted data without additional precautions.

